timeline
    title Evolution of Computing — Key Milestones
    section Foundations (1940s–1960s)
        1945 : ENIAC — first general-purpose electronic computer
             : Von Neumann architecture proposed
        1947 : Transistor invented at Bell Labs
        1956 : First hard disk drive (IBM 305 RAMAC, 5 MB)
             : Dartmouth Conference coins "Artificial Intelligence"
        1958 : Integrated circuit invented independently by Kilby & Noyce
        1964 : IBM System/360 — first family of compatible computers
             : BASIC programming language created
        1969 : ARPANET — first message sent (UCLA → SRI)
             : Unix development begins at Bell Labs
             : Apollo Guidance Computer lands humans on the Moon
    section Personal Computing (1970s–1980s)
        1971 : Intel 4004 — first commercial microprocessor
             : First email sent by Ray Tomlinson
        1973 : Xerox Alto — first PC with a GUI
             : Ethernet invented at Xerox PARC
        1976 : Apple I released by Jobs & Wozniak
        1977 : Apple II, Commodore PET, TRS-80 launch
        1981 : IBM PC launched with MS-DOS
             : First portable computer (Osborne 1, 24 lbs)
        1983 : TCP/IP adopted as ARPANET standard
             : GNU Project announced by Richard Stallman
        1984 : Apple Macintosh — first mass-market GUI computer
             : DNS (Domain Name System) introduced
        1985 : Windows 1.0 released
             : C++ published by Bjarne Stroustrup
    section Internet Age (1990s)
        1990 : Tim Berners-Lee invents the World Wide Web
             : First web server & browser (NeXT computer)
        1991 : Linux kernel released by Linus Torvalds
             : Python 0.9 released by Guido van Rossum
        1993 : Mosaic browser makes WWW accessible to masses
             : NVIDIA founded
        1994 : Amazon founded by Jeff Bezos
             : Netscape Navigator released
        1995 : JavaScript created in 10 days by Brendan Eich
             : Java 1.0 released by Sun Microsystems
             : PHP, Ruby, and MySQL released
             : eBay and Craigslist launch
        1996 : CSS1 specification published
             : Google search project begins at Stanford
        1998 : Google incorporated
             : XML 1.0 becomes W3C recommendation
        1999 : RSS and AJAX concepts emerge
             : Wi-Fi (802.11b) becomes mainstream
    section Cloud & Mobile (2000s)
        2001 : Agile Manifesto published
             : Wikipedia launches
        2004 : Facebook founded
             : Gmail launches with 1 GB storage
             : Ubuntu Linux first release
        2005 : Git created by Linus Torvalds
             : YouTube launches
             : AJAX term coined (Google Maps)
        2006 : AWS launches EC2 and S3
             : Twitter launches
             : jQuery released
        2007 : iPhone released — mobile revolution begins
             : Hadoop initial release
        2008 : Google Chrome browser & V8 engine
             : Android 1.0 released
             : GitHub launches
        2009 : Node.js released by Ryan Dahl
             : Bitcoin whitepaper → genesis block mined
             : Go language released by Google
    section Modern Era (2010s–present)
        2010 : iPad launches
             : Instagram launches (1M users in 2 months)
        2011 : Kubernetes predecessor (Borg) paper published
             : IBM Watson wins Jeopardy!
        2012 : TypeScript released by Microsoft
             : Docker concept emerges
        2013 : React released by Facebook
             : Docker 0.1 released
        2014 : Kubernetes open-sourced by Google
             : AWS Lambda — serverless computing begins
        2015 : TensorFlow open-sourced by Google
             : Rust 1.0 released
             : HTTP/2 standardized
        2017 : Transformer architecture ("Attention Is All You Need")
             : WebAssembly MVP in all major browsers
        2020 : GPT-3 released (175B parameters)
             : GitHub Copilot preview
        2022 : ChatGPT launches (100M users in 2 months)
             : Stable Diffusion open-sourced
        2023 : GPT-4, Claude, Gemini — multimodal AI era
             : WebGPU specification finalized
        2024 : AI agents and autonomous coding assistants
             : Apple Vision Pro — spatial computing
